{meta: title Come On In}
{meta: artist Patsy Cline}
{meta: composer V.F. Stewart}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]Come on in and sit [C]right down and [D7]make yourself at [G]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
If I had one wish I wish I could
[C]Go back to my old neighborhood
[D7]Where the good folks they all love you as their [G]own
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Then I'd go over to my neighbor's house
[C]Knock on the door 'n they'd all sing out
[G]Come on in and sit [C]right down and [D7]make yourself at [G]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
I'd sing their praises long and loud
[C]Cause their all my folks and I'm mighty proud
[D7]Of the little old town back home where I was [G]born
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
I wish that I could hear them say
[C]In the good old-fashioned friendly way
[G]Come on in and sit [C]right down and [D7]make yourself at [G]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
Well they don't lock their doors at night
[C]Cause they all know they're a doing right
[D7]And the good Lord's bound to have them for his [G]own
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
If I'd go back to hear them pray
[C]In the little pine church they all would say
[G]Come on in and sit [C]right down and [D7]make yourself at [G]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
When I was a child of only three
[C]I said my prayers at my mother's knee
[D7]And I knew right then from God I'd never [G]roam
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 9}
When I get my summons on the Judgment Day
[C]I hope I can hear my Savior say
[G]Come on in and sit [C]right down and [D7]make yourself at [G]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 10}
[C]Come on in and sit right [D7]down and make yourself at [G]home
{end_of_verse}
